# Swap Event System Deep Dive

The Swap event system is a **decoupled event-driven architecture** for HTMX applications, allowing you to orchestrate UI updates without tight coupling between components.

In a **layered architecture**, events flow from the **Domain layer** through the **Application layer** to the **Web layer**, enabling clean separation of concerns.

---

## Core Concepts

### What is a Swap Event?

A **Swap Event** is a custom browser event triggered by server responses that tells HTMX elements when to update.

**Traditional approach (tightly coupled):**
```html
<!-- After adding todo, manually refresh list -->
<form hx-post="/Todos/Create" 
      hx-target="#todo-list">
</form>
```

**Swap event approach (decoupled):**
```html
<!-- Form fires event, list listens independently -->
<form hx-post="/Todos/Create" hx-swap="none"></form>

<div id="todo-list" 
     hx-get="/Todos/List"
     hx-trigger="ui.refreshList from:body">
</div>
```

**Benefits:**
- Components don't need to know about each other
- Multiple listeners can react to one action
- Easy to add new behaviors without touching existing code
- Domain layer stays pure (no HTTP/view concerns)

---

## Event Flow in Layered Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Domain Layer                                   │
│  Defines event names (pure strings)             │
│  DomainEvents.TodoCreated = "entity.created:todo"│
└──────────────────┬──────────────────────────────┘
                   │
                   ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Application Layer                              │
│  Fires domain events via IEventBus              │
│  _eventBus.Fire(DomainEvents.TodoCreated)       │
└──────────────────┬──────────────────────────────┘
                   │
                   ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Web Layer (Event Chains)                       │
│  Maps domain events → UI events                 │
│  events.Chain(                                  │
│    DomainEvents.TodoCreated,                    │
│    "ui.refreshList",                            │
│    "ui.showToast")                              │
└──────────────────┬──────────────────────────────┘
                   │
                   ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Browser (HTMX)                                 │
│  Views listen to UI events                      │
│  hx-trigger="ui.refreshList from:body"          │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

---

## Event Naming Convention

Use **namespaced dot notation** for clarity:

```
category.action:entity
```

**Examples:**
- `entity.created:todo` — A todo was created
- `entity.updated:todo` — A todo was updated
- `entity.deleted:todo` — A todo was deleted
- `ui.refresh` — Generic UI refresh
- `ui.refreshList` — Refresh specific list
- `ui.showToast` — Show toast notification
- `filter.changed:status` — Filter status changed

---

## Defining Events in Domain Layer

**Domain layer defines pure event names:**

```csharp
// Domain/Events/DomainEvents.cs
public static class DomainEvents
{
    // Todo events
    public static string TodoCreated => "entity.created:todo";
    public static string TodoUpdated => "entity.updated:todo";
    public static string TodoDeleted => "entity.deleted:todo";
    public static string TodoCompleted => "entity.completed:todo";
    
    // Product events (example)
    public static string ProductCreated => "entity.created:product";
    public static string ProductUpdated => "entity.updated:product";
    public static string ProductDeleted => "entity.deleted:product";
    
    // Helper methods for dynamic entities
    public static string EntityCreated(string entityName) => $"entity.created:{entityName}";
    public static string EntityUpdated(string entityName) => $"entity.updated:{entityName}";
    public static string EntityDeleted(string entityName) => $"entity.deleted:{entityName}";
}
```

**Why in Domain?**
- Domain events represent business occurrences
- No dependencies on infrastructure or frameworks
- Pure strings that Application layer can use

