## Best Practices

✅ **Do:**
- Define domain events in Domain layer (pure strings)
- Fire events from Application layer via `IEventBus`
- Map domain events to UI events in Web layer (event chains)
- Use namespaced naming (`entity.created:todo`, not `todoCreated`)
- Keep event chains simple (2-4 events max)
- Use specific events over generic ones
- Document event flows in `SwapEventChains.cs`

❌ **Don't:**
- Fire events from Domain entities (no infrastructure dependencies)
- Hard-code event names in views (use domain constants)
- Create circular event chains
- Fire too many events from one action
- Use events for synchronous logic (use method calls)
- Couple Application layer to Swap framework (use `IEventBus` abstraction)

---

## Advanced Patterns

### Conditional Event Firing

```csharp
// Application/Services/ProductService.cs
public async Task CreateProductAsync(string name, decimal price, int stock)
{
    var product = new Product { Name = name, Price = price, Stock = stock };
    
    await _repository.AddAsync(product);
    await _repository.SaveChangesAsync();
    
    _eventBus.Fire(DomainEvents.ProductCreated);
    
    // Conditional event
    if (stock < 10)
        _eventBus.Fire(DomainEvents.ProductInventoryLow);
}
```

### Event Aggregation

Combine multiple domain events into one UI event:

```csharp
// Web/Events/SwapEventChains.cs
events.Chain(DomainEvents.TodoCreated, "ui.dataChanged");
events.Chain(DomainEvents.TodoUpdated, "ui.dataChanged");
events.Chain(DomainEvents.TodoDeleted, "ui.dataChanged");
```

Listeners use single event:

```html
<div hx-get="/Dashboard/Summary"
     hx-trigger="ui.dataChanged from:body">
</div>
```

### Event Priority

Fire critical events first:

```csharp
_eventBus.Fire(DomainEvents.OrderCreated); // Primary
_eventBus.Fire(DomainEvents.InventoryReserved); // Secondary
```

